The Iron Compact Appeal was Rakuen's third and most formally prepared annexation petition, submitted eleven years ago during the Modern Tension era.
It differed from previous petitions in institutional preparation: Kiess had certified its legal standing through the inter-city petition review framework, and Mafdet had co-signed as a supporting city.
The petition proposed staged legal integration — a phased annexation schedule designed to avoid sudden administrative shock to either city's systems.
Midgaard refused on constitutional charter-sovereignty grounds: the Charter Sovereignty office held that Midgaard's founding compact did not provide a mechanism for sovereign incorporation of an already-chartered independent city.
The refusal created the most politically complicated outcome of the three petition cycles: Kiess's certification made the refusal a direct confrontation with Kiess's legal authority, not just Rakuen's petition.
Mafdet's co-signature meant the refusal was a five-city political event rather than a bilateral Midgaard-Rakuen decision.
The response to the refusal was indirect compensatory mechanisms: Kowloon's Southern Grain Compact formalization, Kiess's standing charter-consultation offer, and Mafdet's expanded mercy-freight classification, none of which provided annexation.
Three factions emerged in Rakuen's political aftermath: the Amendment Track (seeking to modify Midgaard's charter to create an annexation pathway), the Quiet Separatists (developing maritime independence through Mafdet), and the Preservation Coalition (maintaining current inter-city cooperation without annexation).
The Iron Compact Appeal's petition text is the most legally dense of the three: it cites First Stone Accord language, Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant precedent, Kowloon's Southern Grain Compact obligations, and Mafdet's maritime cargo law in a unified argument that Rakuen's integration serves the five-city network's founding purpose.
Midgaard's charter-sovereignty refusal did not address the substantive argument; it addressed only the constitutional question of whether a mechanism for annexation existed.
A fourth petition is now active in Rakuen politics; the Amendment Track faction is working with Kiess's legal team on whether a Kiess-certified charter amendment could create the mechanism Midgaard's refusal said did not exist.

